1136 To be expended for the Bullying Prevention Project in accordance with Title 16, Chapter 28B,
1137 Code of Alabama 1975. The State Superintendent of Education shall distribute the above
1138 appropriation as grants to local education agencies. These agencies may be awarded funds only
1139 after application to the State Department of Education. The grant application process may
1140 require the submission of plans by the applicant to meet the requirements set forth in Chapter
1141 28B of Title 16. In the awarding of grants, preference will be given to applicants seeking to
1142 develop and implement evidence-based practices to promote a school environment that is free of
1143 harassment, intimidation, violence, and threats of violence. This program may also address tier
1144 one and tier two of the school-based mental health model of all students receiving prevention
1145 education and peers working to support and identify at-risk students. Additionally, the program
1146 may focus to increase school safety through early identification of at-risk students,
1147 minimizing disciplinary infractions including school suspensions and expulsions. The program
1148 may provide grade level prevention curriculum for all students and, in that case, the
1149 curriculum must be updated annually to remain current and relevant to current trends that youth
1150 face in their lives. Any applicable prevention curriculum must be comprehensive and satisfy the
1151 following state mandates: Erin's Law, Jamari Terrell Williams Student Bullying Prevention Act,
1152 Jason Flatt Act, Price Hornsby Act, and drugs and alcohol prevention programs. In addition, any
1153 program related to mental health should be flexible enough to focus on the greatest mental
1154 health needs for each individual school. For accountability purposes, reporting data must
1155 include the number of students engaged in the programs, the number of students supported, and
1156 the number of students referred to adults as at-risk.
