1186 This appropriation shall be used for the State Department of Education, in consultation with
1187 the Department of Early Childhood Education, to fund a program to be known as the Governor's
1188 Turnaround Schools. These grants are for the lowest performing public elementary schools which
1189 are identified as underperforming by the State Superintendent in consideration of the
1190 provisions of the Alabama Accountability Act, the State Report Card System, and other criteria
1191 as determined by the State Superintendent. The intent of these grants is to identify and target
1192 specific deficiencies of each individual underperforming elementary school and target said
1193 deficiencies with high quality and innovative educational supports. In consultation with these
1194 schools as well as the local education agencies that respectively oversee these schools, the
1195 State Department of Education will develop and oversee a comprehensive plan for school
1196 improvement. It is the intention of this provision that all areas of the State Department,
1197 including Alabama Reading Initiative, Alabama Math, Science, and Technology Initiative, Office
1198 of Mathematics Improvement, and Office of School Improvement, will work together to best serve
1199 these selected schools. Schools previously named to this list will be known as Cohort 1.
1200 Beginning with the fiscal year 2027 Budget Request, the State Department will recommend a
1201 pathway for schools in Cohort 1 to exit this program, and the Department will recommend new
1202 schools to replace those exiting the program in subsequent years. These schools may be known as
1203 Cohort 2 and so forth. The State Superintendent may also request additional funds so that
1204 additional cohorts can be expanded as Cohort 1 schools leave the program over the next few
1205 years. Any expansion of new Cohorts should be modest with respect to the purpose of this
1206 program which is expected to offer extraordinary supports to a relatively limited number of
1207 schools at a time. The State Department of Education should annually produce written progress
1208 reports on these schools to the Chair of the House Ways and Means - Education Committee, the
